<br>
Lets use the stats for the<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Orbital Test Vehicle</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as listed on<br>
page 55 of the Project Orion book by George Dyson:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Orbital Test Vehicle</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
·Gross Weight: - 880 tons<br>
<br>
·Propulsion System empty weight<br>
 (pusher, shock absorbers, storage and delivery) - 370 tons<br>
<br>
·Diameter - 80 ft (it was the 1960's so it's not metric!)<br>
<br>
·Height - 120 ft<br>
<br>
·Average total acceleration of ship - 2 g<br>
<br>
·Number of pulses to reach 300 mile orbit - 800<br>
<br>
·Total yield to reach 300 mile orbit - .450 to 1.8 MT<br>
<br>
·ISP = 3000 sec.<br>
<br>
·Payload 300 mile orbit (V = 10km/sec) - 300 tons <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/8/02 7:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=67.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.anigifs.de/Augen/Augen_2/Auge_von_Frau_53_4KB.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/alien.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Chem Orions</span><hr size=1> A chem Orion would be totally pointless.<br>
Think about a bullet. <br>
How would you propel that bullet with gunpowder?<br>
Would you:<br>
1) explode a gram of gunpowder in space next to the bullet?<br>
or<br>
2) detonate the explosive in a sealed tube with the bullet next to it?<br>
<br>
The answer is #2<br>
<br>
The ONLY reason one would use the incredibly inefficient design of an external pulse engine is due to the nature of an atomic bomb explosion. <br>
A properly designed non-accelerator based engine uses a thrust chamber/nozzle system.<br>
